title: add a component that connects FavoriteButton to redux
message:
add a component that connects FavoriteButton to redux

Adding this as a separate component allows us to potentially re-use the "favorite" component
somewhere else later on, where we'll only need to re-connect it to redux or wherever the data
comes from.

title: remove SAVE_FAVORITE_BUILDINGS action in favor of TOGGLE_FAVORITE_BUILDING andâ€¦
message:
remove SAVE_FAVORITE_BUILDINGS action in favor of TOGGLE_FAVORITE_BUILDING and LOAD_FAVORITE_BUILDINGS

LOAD_FAVORITE_BUILDINGS is a single-purpose action that loads the favorites from AsyncStorage
and tells the reducer to store them.

TOGGLE_FAVORITE_BUILDING is a much fancier action creator, that gets the current set of
favorited buildings from the redux state and uses that to add or remove the given building
name from the set of favorites, and then re-sort the list of buildings.

It also has to save the favorites to AsyncStorage, because there's no better place to perform
the actual "save" (yet).

title: remove fetchData call from StatefulList.render
message: remove fetchData call from StatefulList.render

title: switch to functional array manipulation in groupBuildings
message:
switch to functional array manipulation in groupBuildings

We avoid manual array manipulation in the app, in favor of the .map/.reduce functions.

You can see how the first loop, which builds up an array of favorited buildings, can be
replaced with a single line Array#filter call that "filters" down the existing array to just
the items we're interested in. I also merged the array creation with the group creation on
the previous line.

Then, later, we had some array manipulation to build up the total set of groups to show; I
replaced the if-and-loop with a single if that contains an "array spread" to prepend the
Favorites group if we need to.

title: update the favoriteBuildings check in stateful-list
message:
update the favoriteBuildings check in stateful-list

If `state.buildings` exists, `state.buildings.favoriteBuildings` is guaranteed to exist.

We need to check if `state.buildings` itself exists, so that's what this commit does.

title: remove empty anonymous function call from FavoriteButton
message:
remove empty anonymous function call from FavoriteButton

If you just pass a reference to a function without calling it, it's synonymous to passing an
anonymous function that passes no arguments.

That is, `prop={() => {func()}}` is nearly equivalent to `prop={func}` for almost all intents
and purposes.

title: mimic calendar's refreshing behavior in student-orgs
message:
mimic calendar's refreshing behavior in student-orgs

That is, the view is loading by default. Every time getData runs, it sets "loading" to false,
which is a noop after the first render.

title: rework the propagate_version action
message:
rework the propagate_version action

It now takes the place of the set_version action, as well.

It takes the version from package.json and writes it into the gradle and
Xcode config files, thereby allowing us to never need to update those
version numbers.

This will allow us to release a new version entirely from GitHub, as
we'll be able to just update the version in package.json and make a new
release, without needing any command-line tools.

title: fix :CFBundleIdentifier Not Found error
message:
fix :CFBundleIdentifier Not Found error

It turns out that the React Native CLI was looking for the app bundle under the
name "AllAboutOlaf", but the bundle's name was "All About Olaf" (with spaces.)

What I did was to change the bundle identifier to the no-space version, then add
the spaced version as the Display Name for the app target. Now the CLI is happy,
and our users are happy because the app still has spaces in its homescreen name.

message:

so that we don't accidentally cause re-renders because we provided an arrow function to onPress.

* throw an error if android tab has no render method

* rework the "make tabs fill the view" feature on android

It turns out thatTabBar renders the tabs to fill the width of the window when scrollEnabled
is false.

* add initialLayout to android tabbed-view

it apparently avoids a one-frame jank where the view has to measure itself

* only render screens within two tabs of the current tab on android

* collapse a line

title: <FilterView/> component (#467)
message:
<FilterView/> component (#467)

* Add a FilterView component

Usage:
<FilterView
  // a path to the filters stored in Redux somewhere
  pathToFilters={['menus', 'stav']}
  // you need to do something with the changes
  onChange={filters => doSomething()}
/>

In React parlance, FilterView is a "controlled component" â€“ it will only
ever render what it is given, and it does not maintain any state itself.

It can render two types of filter, a Toggle and a List. Types for those
are provided in `types.js`.

* Add an `applyFiltersToItem` function

Usage: arr.filter(item => applyFiltersToItem(filters, item))

Applies all filters in `filters` to `item`. Returns `true` if they pass,
and `false` if any fail.

title: Add iOS beta-deployment abilities to Travis (#414)
message:
Add iOS beta-deployment abilities to Travis (#414)

* add `fastlane ios update_match`

to forcibly run match and update the provisioning profiles

* consolidate the keychain setup into a fastlane lane

this is just simpler than letting it spread out over everything.

* make `fastlane ios build` available

because travis is still failing to run the UI tests

fastlane readme

* add `fastlane ios screenshot` command

also updates the Snapfile to put the screenshots in the .gitignored place

* fix operator precedence issue in fastfile

* encode some build information in the changelog

add the branch and hash to the changelog.

also updates the changelog to report all commits since last build.

* change match repo url to https

Travis and the Deploy Key approach recommend (require?) the use of https
instead of git+ssh.

* fix android increment_version_code action path

increment_version_code uses a glob to look for the build.gradle file,
but it takes the first one it finds - in a pattern like
'**/$app_folder_name/*/build.gradle'

So we're doing two things here:
- restricting the glob to the build.gradle we want,
- and removing the "./" from the pattern so it will match the paths

* ignore ruby deps from android builds

* update fastlane

* fix hockeysdk installation script

* remove bitrise config

* update travis config and steps

- adds ios builds back to travis
- allows automatic once-daily betas from travis (via cron)
- uses fastlane to build both ios and android
- adds a js-bundling test to the js builds
- only pings coveralls after the js build

Some more info: I realized that the caches, and `before_cache`
instructions, didn't need to be different per-platform â€“ node_modules
should be cached everywhere, for instance.

That allowed me to get rid of the yaml references.

I also upgraded the js builds to the new "trusty" beta. Not much
difference there. The android builds are still on "precise", because the
android stuff isn't available on trusty yet.

I converted the env configs into objects, to let travis turn them into
the strings for us, and I renamed some of them, preferring lowercase keys.

OS X has been upgraded to Sierra and Xcode 8.1.

Travis will now spawn a cron-job to trigger a build once a day; this
build will release a new beta.

I've started exporting the api key into the build, if we're going to
deploy.

I added a JS bundle step to the js builds.

That's about it.

title: Calendar update (#305)
message:
Calendar update (#305)

* Remove unnessary functions

I like the new pattern of putting the arrow functions in the listviews, so I chaged it to use that.

* Re-format dates so that we are not showing past days at the top of the calendar

The old system used the start day of multi-day events to display the event, even if that day had passed. It looked really silly to have "Sept. 7" at the top of the calendar still, so I force it to use today.

* Add missing braces to statement

Missing braces to "if" statement fixed.

message:
Add iOS notifications (#161)

* Remove ride-along change

Didn't intend for that to be in here, was just faster to make another commit than to revert.

* Use relative paths

Xcode used absolute paths. I want to use relative paths. I am smarter than Xcode.

* Make Travis work with Cocoapods (#164)

* Change the test command to use the workspace file

* switch to xcodebuild

* Revert "switch to xcodebuild"

fc5fa3e8fc3e852598227be56ebdabc07866b10b

* switch to just building iOS

* Add iOS notifications

Using Cocoapods to add the code driving the OneSignal service for the notificaitons. The backend is registering the simulator that I'm using for iOS testing, but since simulators cannot get notificaitons I haven't seen the end-to-end process work yet. I'll be able to do that within the day and will make an update if it's not working as expected.

open/close times.

message: Merge travis into master

title: disable incremental compilation on travis?
message: disable incremental compilation on travis?

title: enable a more extensive build matrix on travis
message:
enable a more extensive build matrix on travis

- js builds only need js tooling, so we use travis' docker-based
  containers for fast boot. this trims the runtime for js-tests from
  around 3-4 minutes to about 45-50 seconds.

- android builds have a dedicated `android` environment that we can take
  advantage of. use it. this drops the time from ~20 minutes to ~9.

- i added the tooling to support running an android emulator on the new
  builds. however, it takes about 20 minutes to run the android tests on
  this system because of the emulator. when we decide to build more
  tests for the emulator, this will be useful.

- os x / ios builds still use the same image.

title: Add CI Integration â€“ Travis and Appveyor (#39)
message:
Add CI Integration â€“ Travis and Appveyor (#39)

* add a bunch of npm run-scripts to do things

- added "flow" â€“ will eventually run flow on the code
- added "bundle:{ios,android}" â€“ just bundles the code for ios/android
- added "build:{ios,android:{macos,win}}" â€“ builds the app binary
- added "test:js" - will run jest tests, when we have them
- added "test" - runs the "flow" and "test:js" commands
- added "test:ios" - runs the default ios native xctests
- added placeholders for test:android and release scripts

* add an appveyor config file

* add a travis-ci config file

* Add keys.js creation to the config files

* Add test to work around the android build failing

title: accommodate a breaking change in rn@0.28 wrt/flexWrap and alignItems
message:
accommodate a breaking change in rn@0.28 wrt/flexWrap and alignItems

see https://github.com/facebook/react-native/releases/tag/v0.28.0

> Due to performance tweaks flexWrap: wrap no longer works together with
> alignItems: 'stretch' (the default). If you use flexWrap: wrap you
> probably will want to add the alignItems: 'flex-start' style as well.
